MAPGD allele frequencies

We used MAPGD to identify polymorphic sites in the pool-seq data and to estimate the frequency of the major allele. As a sanity check lets take a look at the allele frequenct distribution.

The MAPGD ouptut file is gzip compressed. It consists of two major blocks: 1) a list of the contigs and their lengths, 2) a tab separated table consisting of:

  • Scaffold name
  • Position
  • Reference base
  • Major allele base
  • Minor allele base
  • Total coverage
  • Estimated error
  • s columns od results, one column per sample. Fields in the sample results are separated by /.

The MAPGD documentation seems to be a bit out of date on the contents of these columns, but the first field is the allele frequency. Which allele is not specified, but it appears to be the reference allele. MAPGD uses samtools mpileup output as its input. Because mpileup does not include sample identifiers, there are no sample identifers in the MAPGD output. Samples should bwe in the same order they were given to mpileup.

The two major blocks of the output file are separated by comments starting with an @ character.

Read in the data.

First w need to figure out where the second block of the oupt file is located. Grep will do this.

zgrep -n "^@" allpops.mapgd.out.22.gz
## 1:@NAME:REGIONS  VERSION:0.4.40  FORMAT:TEXT CONCATENATED
## 2:@NAME              LENGTH
## 28646:@END_TABLE
## 28647:@NAME:POOL VERSION:0.4.40  FORMAT:TEXT CONCATENATED    INDEXED
## 28648:@SCFNAME           POS REF MAJOR   MINOR   COVRAG  ERROR   /mpileup.out.gz:1   /mpileup.out.gz:2   /mpileup.out.gz:3   /mpileup.out.gz:4   /mpileup.out.gz:5   /mpileup.out.gz:6   /mpileup.out.gz:7   /mpileup.out.gz:8
## 3323679:@END_TABLE

So, skip the first 28648 lines.

Read the data from file

dat <- read.table(file = gzfile("allpops.mapgd.out.22.gz"),
                  header = F,
                  comment.char = "@",
                  skip = 28648,
                  col.names = c("scaffold", "position", "ref", "major", "minor", "coverage", "error", "B", "D", "H", "K", "L", "O", "S", "T"))

Plot Allele frequencies

Use stringr to extract the allele freqs

library(stringr)

For each site, plot the folded site frequency spectrum for the minor allele. Need purrr::map2 for that.

library(purrr)

Site B

Get the minor allele frequency

freqs <- as.numeric(str_split_i(dat$B, "/", 1))
maf <- unlist(map2(freqs, 1 - freqs, min))

Plot the folded site frequency spectrum

hist(maf,
     main = "Minor allele frequency",
     col = "steelblue2")

Conclusion

The folded SFS for each location is very much not what we expect for a neutral process (most alleles are rare). It looks to me like MAPGD is heavily biasing detection to sites with high expected heterozygosity.
